This paper discusses the adaptation of different subsystems of organisms over different time scales, and how a minimal yet embodied model of development can increase evolvability in robots. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Robotics (cs.RO) sub-category, as it deals with the adaptation of robots. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of machine learning techniques to implement the model, which suggests that it may also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of heterochronic mutations to "lock in" body plans, which suggests that it may belong to the Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-category. The paper also discusses the interaction between development and evolution, which suggests that it may belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the use of theories to explain how development can aid evolution, which suggests that it may also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category.
